{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3e9a5139-0ac0-45e1-9f3d-cdcbabf6dcea","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n- **User crashes:** `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n- **System crashes:** `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName-YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS.ips`.\n\n**Quick lookup:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n**For core dumps** (if needed for `lldb`):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nRun your app again — the core file will appear in `/cores/`.\n\n> 💡 If you need to symbolicate the `.ips` crash log against .NET runtime symbols, consider using the `apple-crash-symbolication` workflow with `atos` and Microsoft's symbol server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f5e570f2-8c9c-4dcc-b2ee-67cee67bfa63","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase or run tools. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":326,"requestId":"1B84:114B45:DD6833:FCB727:6A028690"},"id":"6edbbb00-691c-44a5-b878-a7de9331f71f","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:47:06.026Z","parentId":"8a266033-2b80-43cd-aff7-f30ae7c59622"}
